              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>because it guides directly to acknowledging of God, as our<lb/> Thora said:\n                    <add>ברכות לב לעולם יסדר אדם שבחו של הקב\"ה ואח\"כ יתפלל</add><lb/> (<add>איפא\n                    פנימיו אומר אם תפילה של אדם נשמעת אלא בבית הכנסת שנאמר לשמוע אל הרנה ואל</add>)\n                If our prayers be Hymns and praises, the<lb/> subjective effect is a direct display\n                of God's divine character<lb/> but if our prayers are supplanting or reporting our\n                own foo-<lb/>lishness or <sic>weekness</sic> are the direct, and God's omnipotence\n                and<lb/> mercy the indirect display. Therefore hymns are the former<lb/> and prayers\n                the latter part of our service.</p>\n            <p><hi rend=\"underline\">b</hi> If the effect of prayer is subjective, we want in\n                them<lb/> no mediation between God and man, neither of the angels nor<lb/> of other\n                spiritual beings.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">\n                <add>התפילה במקום הרנה רש\"י קלוסו של ישראל שם תהיה התפילה</add>\n            </p>\n            <p>It is said in the Talmud <add>ברכות דק ד</add><lb/> The <add>ריב\"ל</add> and the\n                    <add>כאשר נעמוד על סוף כונת התפילה נמצא שיש בה בו בחינות הא' לספר בשבחו של הקב\"ה\n                    ולהאמין</add> are throughout against the mediation<lb/>\n                <add>כי הוא יכול על כול שהוא מלך מלכי המלכים אשר בידו נפש כל חי. ויש עוד בחינה בו\n                    שהוא</add><lb/> This is the sublime character of our Religion, displaying<lb/>\n                us the purest and most perfect notion of God, of the features<lb/> of his holy\n                existence; guiding us the way to his perfection,<lb/> she also represents us the\n                possible perfection of man by<lb/> the precepts of the revelation, for only to his\n                likeness can<lb/> God speak; by the precepts. In the Likeness of God in his own<lb/>\n                image the man was created, sons are you to the Living God,<lb/> our holy doctrine\n                taught us the perfection of the human <add>?</add><lb/> that the man is the next\n                intellectual being to God, he is his<lb/> son, that he can acknowledge God and serve\n                him without one<lb/> mediation. No religion in the whole world possesses those\n                high<lb/> terms of truth, trust and eternal hopes. The Psalmist was<lb/> inspired by\n                those Deas and sung so lovely <add>ראשונה כפי סברת המוני והוא השגת תכלית מבוקשו, אך\n                    אתן שינוי לבתי אדון כל</add>.<lb/> But those high notions make us very easily\n                proud or haughty,<lb/> therefore we need to be <sic>remined</sic> of our\n                foolishness, meekness,<lb/> transitoriness, invalidity and nullity, that shall be\n                done<lb/> by our prayers of supplication and <sic>repentence</sic>, and not<lb/> by\n                the notion of the mediation (that was the first reason of it)<lb/> for this is an\n                Sea guise strangely to our holy Religion.</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/canvas/p2"
                }
