              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p><hi rend=\"underline\">C</hi> If the effect of our prayers shall be subjective,\n                our<lb/> service ought to be in the <sic>hebrew</sic> language—for<lb/> this\n                language is the tongue of our Prophets, of our<lb/> solemn Psalmists, the tongue of\n                our holy scripture.<lb/> yea, the mere <sic>soun</sic> of those words awake our\n                heart<lb/> to a holier feeling and higher inspiration, to a<lb/> sublime admiration\n                of the most High. There exists no<lb/> language, that possesses a character so\n                sublime and ador<lb/>ing, simple and short, easy and living, this is the<lb/> best\n                vehicle of our thoughts before God. And again,<lb/> no poetry had so aft and\n                manifold the Deity to her<lb/> object, nor sung so solemnly the attributes and\n                perfections<lb/> of God, as the <sic>hebrew</sic> did; there is no poetry\n                possessing<lb/> those riches of natural picturesque and scenery, which breath<lb/>\n                love and admiration in the heart. Those sentimental<lb/>\n                <del>sentim</del> sentences of the prophets, those <sic>conserated</sic> and\n                deeply<lb/> felt words of the holy Scripture are the best vehicle <del>?</del><lb/>\n                to adore our God. And again we ought to understand the<lb/> words of our heart, and\n                where is the son of <placeName>Israel</placeName>, who<lb/> understands not the\n                language of his Thora? If some<lb/> should be so unhappy to be ignorant in the word\n                of his<lb/> holy book, they may weep and study, as our ancestors did<lb/> in the\n                time of <persName>Esra</persName>, but for the benefit of some we<lb/> can'nt offer\n                the whole</p>\n            <p><hi rend=\"underline\">D</hi> All those prayers of reaangenie<add>?</add> or curses\n                need to be expelled<lb/> of our liturgy, what subjective effect can we expect of them?<lb/>\n                <add>שמות לג, כ כי לא יראני האדם וחי</add>.</p>\n            <p><hi rend=\"underline\">E</hi> The sabbatical morning-service shall not be\n                continued<lb/> above 2 ½ or 3 hours including the sermon, and that of the<lb/>\n                festivals not above 3 or 3 ½ hours (Rabbi did not speak of<lb/> a service without\n                sermon) It is said in the Talmud, that <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Akiba</persName> and\n                    <persName>Rabbi Atarphon</persName> made their prayers<lb/> very short, when\n                they ministered in the Synagogue<lb/>\n                <add>ברוך ובלבבך לעשותו כי קרוב אליך הדבר מאוד</add></p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/canvas/p3"
                }
