              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/manifest/annotation/p8",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(center)\">\n                <placeName>Albany</placeName>\n                <date>March 14. 1851</date>\n            </p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Dear Sir</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(2)\">Your favor of the <date>12.</date> ins. was duly<lb/> received, and\n                I take pleasure in answering you instantly.<lb/> You find the best account about the\n                school of <placeName>Padua</placeName> in<lb/>\n                <persName>Dr. I. M Josts</persName>\n                <add>?</add><lb/>\n                <add>?</add>; in his <add>?</add><lb/>\n                <add>?</add> you find only a brief sketch,<lb/> while the former book contains an\n                    <sic>authentical</sic> and perfect<lb/> historical account gathered from the\n                written documents<lb/> of that school. As to the statement of\n                    <persName>Hollam</persName> that<lb/>\n                <date>1350</date> be the date of its foundation I have to observe, that<lb/> this is\n                by no means correct; for if he refers to the<lb/> rabbinic-cabalistic school, which\n                once was a <placeName>Padua</placeName> and<lb/> which was the foundation of the\n                present one, we could<lb/> show him in the different prefaces of rabbinical and<lb/>\n                cabalistic treatises that this school existed already in<lb/> the <date>10<hi\n                        rend=\"sup\">th</hi> century</date>, as you will find in\n                    <persName>Josts</persName>; and the<lb/> present one was founded by exiles from\n                    <placeName>Spain</placeName>, or<lb/> rather the old one was gradually converted\n                into a<lb/> scientific institute by those intelligent <sic>spanish</sic>\n                <sic>jews</sic>,<lb/> which was at the commencement of the <date>15<hi rend=\"sup\"\n                        >th</hi> century</date>.<lb/> Were I not too much employed otherwise I would\n                fur<lb/>nish you with a sketch; but I think it is too interesting<lb/> as that you\n                should allow one to do it for you.</p>\n            <p>You will be kind enough to excuse me, that I would not<lb/> write any thing about\n                    <sic>jewish</sic>\n                <sic>juris prudence</sic>; I retired<lb/> altogether from the field of\n                    <sic>jewish</sic> literature for various<lb/> reasons. I was beaten every way\n                and with all sorts of<lb/> rods; I was decried by all sorts of fanatics, fools, ignorants,<lb/>\n                <add>?</add>; I was rejected, abused wherever I opened the door;<lb/> I found that\n                men as <persName>Mr. Isaac</persName>, <persName>Mr. Lyon</persName>, <persName>Mr.\n                    Rosen-<lb/>feld</persName>, and others, who have knowledge enough to read<lb/>\n                the prayers and humbug the world with an assumed<lb/> bigotry, with some dozens of\n                every day sentences, which<lb/> they compile to a sort of speech, and repeat\n                them</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p39z90z3v/canvas/p8"
                }
              ]
